	isbn = {978-1-5386-7619-6},
	abstract = {Taxi demand prediction is to predict the number of taxis needed in given zones at a certain time. However, it is becoming much more needed and useful to predict where the passengers would probably go and how many, i.e. their probable destinations and the amount. We call such prediction as refined taxi demand prediction, which seldom researches paid on. This is due to the increasingly popular real-time ride sharing, which is an economical and environment-friendly way to call taxis. Such refined taxi demand prediction would improve service quality and user experience. In this paper, we propose a method named ST-Vec, which maps zones with dense low-dimensional vectors (embedding) sustaining their spatio-temporal relationships of taxi demand, i.e. the more probable destination zones of taxi demand from a given zones, their vectors would be closer. By such method, the spatio-temporal relationships of taxi demand in zones can be measured in terms of geometric distance between the respective vectors. By combining this with multi-outputs support vector regression (MSVR) model, we obtain a robust refined taxi demand prediction model and verify it on the New York City taxi trip dataset.},
